absolute best! - Dr. Jones


The Procedure
As you recline or lye down, dependent upon the area where you will be treated, the pulse dye laser will deliver an intense but gentle burst of light into selectively targeted areas of the skin to target the aforementioned problems. Most patients report a warming or tingling sensation during treatment. No anesthesia is required but it may be used if requested. Candela’s laser also offers an innovative cooling method, which mists the skin before the laser emits its pulse, in an effort to minimize discomfort.
 
BEFORE & AFTER | BACK TO PROCEDURES  

 
 
 
 
 
 

Advanced Superficial Radiation Therapy

Keloids are a type of painful and/or itchy scar tissue that may form over a wound from an injury or surgical procedure. They can also form due to a piercing, acne, chickenpox and even a scratch. Most often, they appear on the chest, back, shoulders and earlobes. Keloids are 15 times more frequent in highly pigmented ethnic groups than in Caucasians. Living with keloids can be difficult and even embarrassing. Surgery alone is usually not the best option as the keloid may grow back and re-form in the scar area, at times recurring larger than the initial growth. 

  I'm always pleased 
when I help my clients
gain the confidence
of knowing they
look their
absolute best! - Dr. Jones


The Procedure Always offering the most advanced treatment options, Lexington Plastic Surgeons is offering Sensus Healthcare’s Superficial Radiotherapy (SRT-100) system for the treatment of keloids. A non-invasive and virtually pain free treatment option, it achieves excellent outcomes when combined with surgery.
The treatment is low-energy radiotherapy whose superficial x-rays pinpoint and concentrate the radiation dose only within the depth of the affected area. The treatment leaves minimal to no scarring and lessens the chance for recurrence.
We understand your struggle with keloids and with this technology we can help you combat the pain and help you look your best.
 
